\begin_layout Standard
Following the conclusion of the preliminary shock-vortex interaction experimenta
l campaign, several obstacles appeared while processing high-speed PLIF
 and PIV image sequences to extract density and velocity fields.
 Because of a slow leak in the miniature shock tube (MST) driven section
 which was not detected until near the end of the experimental campaign,
 the argon in that section was contaminated by a varying amount of nitrogen.
 This made it difficult to perform the iterative correction procedure needed
 for accurate estimation of the acetone concentration, preventing calculation
 of the density field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PIV image sequences exhibit large particle displacements in the up-welling
 region along the centerline of the entrainment bubble, with pre-shock displacem
ents on the order of 60-80 pixels, and post-shock displacements several
 times larger.
 Although an attempt was made to take advantage of the theoretically well-descri
bed vortex-induced velocity field for a displacement estimate, these displacemen
ts proved too large for a state-of-the-art multi-pass PIV processing procedure
 with robust phase correlation and iterative window deformation.
